# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akatarawa-forest
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand is the largest user of 1080 poison, using about 80% of the world's supply.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Biodegradable 1080 poison is the only poison currently registered for use on mainland New Zealand as suitable for aerial targeting of the common brushtail possum; a major conservation and agricultural pest.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand has used 1080 for pest control since the late 1950s; it imports sodium fluoroacetate in raw form from the United States of America.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand is unusual in that it has no naturally occurring extant terrestrial mammal, except for two species of bat.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Similarly, no confirmed fossils of terrestrial mammals have been found in New Zealand from the 85 million years since the landmass split away from Gondwana (except for the St Bathans mammal which is of unclear lineage).
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] As such, New Zealand’s fauna and flora evolved in the absence of mammals and generally didn’t develop the evolutionary strategies needed to avoid predation by mammals.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] When human activity accidentally or deliberately introduced numerous species of invasive mammalian predators to New Zealand (most notably including rats, brush-tailed possums, cats and mustelids) many of New Zealand’s native species were unable to respond and were preyed upon.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Because of this, the introduction of mammalian predators is strongly linked to the decline of New Zealand’s fauna and flora, having a disastrous effect on the populations of many iconic species including kiwi, tuatara and giant wētā.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Because of the continuing impacts of mammalian predators in New Zealand, there is a strong need to utilise a range of specialised predator control tactics to protect New Zealand’s species, including the usage of 1080.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The largest users of 1080 in New Zealand are the Animal Health Board and the Department of Conservation (DOC).
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is also used on a smaller scale for pest control by Regional Councils and private landowners.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The first trials were carried out in New Zealand in 1954, and by 1957 its use had become widespread.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 baits are used through ground-based and aerial application.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 is considered to be suitable for use as a mammalian pest control in New Zealand because the country has only two native land mammals (bats).
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 is commonly used in Western Australia to kill feral carnivores, as the compound is naturally occurring in Western Australian flora and the native herbivores and their native predators are immune.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] When correctly applied, 1080 is very effective at controlling conservation pests.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] One aerial application can kill 98% of possums and more than 90% of rats in the targeted area.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] These successful knock-down rates provide vulnerable native birds with a crucial breeding window to raise chicks through to fledging, increasing their survival rate.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The DOC uses aerially applied 1080 poison across about 440,000 ha of conservation land each year.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] This equates to 5% of the total conservation estate.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] DOC's pest control programme is governed by *residual trap catch* rates, the percentage of nights in which a trap catches a pest.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Targets are usually set to less than 5%, though rates below 2% can be achieved by 1080.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In New Zealand, the common brushtail possum was the main vector for the spread of bovine tuberculosis—a highly contagious disease affecting farmed cattle and deer.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The disease was endemic in possums across about 38% of New Zealand (known as 'vector risk areas') but industry sources acknowledge the incidence of bovine TB fell to less than 0.05% in the areas where it is monitored.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The organisation responsible for managing bovine TB in New Zealand, the Animal Health Board, uses 1080 poison as one of a range of pesticides to kill possums and control the spread of disease to both livestock and unaffected areas of the country.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Aerial application of 1080 poison is only used in places where ground control methods are impractical or unable to reduce possum numbers to a low enough level to break the disease cycle.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In 2011, this was less than 10% of the total area receiving possum control.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Both aerial and ground-based application of 1080 poison are also used to control rabbits, an introduced grazing pest.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] By 1960, it had become the main poison used in rabbit control.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The combination of aerial spreading and the use of carrots poisoned with 1080 enabled rabbit boards (which were responsible for rabbit destruction work) to reduce rabbit numbers in most areas by the early 1960s.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The use of 1080 poison in New Zealand has been the subject of a long and complex debate.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In general, the majority of conservationists and livestock farmers support the continued use of 1080 for pest control, while the hunting community, animal rights groups and antifluoride campaigners support a ban, although there are exceptions on both sides.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Organised opposition is usually small-scale and localised to areas where aerial 1080 operations are carried out.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Protest is generally peaceful, but there have been occasions where opponents have resorted to violence or sabotage.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In August 2007, the Environmental Risk Management Authority released a review that gave new guidelines for the use of 1080 in New Zealand, and concluded the beneficial effects of pest eradication outweighed the risks.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] 1080 decomposes in natural water and soil into harmless compounds.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In June 2011, the Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment (PCE) released a report in favour of 1080 to control possums, rats, and stoats, especially in large and remote areas.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is seen as an effective poison for aerial spreading.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The PCE came to a number of conclusions, including not having a moratorium on 1080 use, and setting up a Game Animal Council.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In 2004, anti-1080 activist Phillip Anderton posed for the New Zealand media with a kiwi he claimed had been poisoned.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] An investigation revealed that Anderton lied to journalists and the public.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] He had used a kiwi that had been caught in a possum trap.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In 2015, the New Zealand Police revealed that anonymous blackmail threats were sent to Fonterra and Federated Farmers saying that infant formula in supermarkets would be poisoned unless the use of 1080 was halted by the end of the month.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Fonterra responded by working with the Ministry for Primary Industries to develop two high-throughput, validated test methods and then testing every tanker of milk and every batch of infant formula for 1080.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The ensuing police response *Operation Concord* led to charges laid against 60-year-old businessman Jeremy Hamish Kerr, who pleaded guilty to two charges of blackmail and was sentenced to 8 years 6 months imprisonment.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Kerr had developed a rival brand of poison called Feratox and made the threats for financial gain.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The court heard that Kerr received around $100,000 a year in royalties from Feratox, but sales were dwindling.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Biodegradable 1080 poison is the only pesticide currently registered for use on mainland New Zealand as suitable for aerial targeting of possums.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] While many research teams are actively seeking new and supplemental approaches to current technologies, no method has yet gained widespread acceptance as a viable alternative to 1080.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] New Zealand currently spends at least $8 million annually on improving existing pest control technology and developing new methods.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] According to the EPA's Annual Report on the Aerial Use of 1080, as of October 2011 there are currently over 50 research projects underway industry-wide to find improvements in the use of 1080, alternatives to 1080 and other related topics.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can the method increase populations of native species?
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can the method rapidly knock down erupting populations of pests?
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can the method be used on a large scale in remote areas?
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Is the method sufficiently cost-effective?
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Does the method leave residues in the environment?
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Can by-kill from the method be minimised?
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment's conclusion with regards to 1080 was, "It is not perfect, but given how controversial it remains, I for one expected that it would not be as effective and safe as it is".
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The Parliamentary Commissioner reached the following conclusions regarding the possible alternatives to 1080 poison currently available in New Zealand.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Pindone, diphacinone, and coumatetralyl are the first-generation anticoagulants most commonly used for pest control.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] They are generally very effective at controlling rats to keep their numbers low, but cannot effectively deal with sudden population surges.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Anticoagulants break down very slowly in water and soil.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] They also accumulate in the liver tissue of live animals that have been exposed to the poison (either by eating bait or feeding on an animal that has eaten bait) and in carcasses.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] They are also the most inhumane of the poisons currently used.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] By-kill of native species is a significant risk from the use of first-generation anticoagulants.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Different types of anticoagulants need to be rotated to avoid populations becoming bait-shy or building up resistance.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Brodifacoum is a second-generation anticoagulant.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is licensed for killing possums and rats.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Like 1080, it will kill stoats that feed on poisoned animals.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It has been successfully used in aerial operations to completely eradicate possums, rats, and stoats on several offshore islands and fenced 'mainland islands' that are now sanctuaries for endangered animals, but it is not currently registered in New Zealand for general aerial use on the mainland.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Brodifacoum takes a very long time to break down in soil and water and accumulates in the tissue of exposed animals for years.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Consequently, there is a very high risk of by-kill: it is known to have killed at least 21 species of native birds, including kiwi, kākā, kākāriki and tūī.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is also widely considered a very inhumane poison.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cyanide has been used in New Zealand since the 1940s, and is licensed for killing possums and wallabies.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is a highly lethal, broad-spectrum poison that depletes cells of energy, quickly resulting in respiratory arrest and death.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Ground-laid cyanide has killed native species and other animals in the past (including kiwi, kea, weka, and bats) and it takes only a tiny amount of cyanide to kill a human.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] While there are antidotes to cyanide poisoning, their effectiveness is controversial and the rapid action of the poison limits the time in which they can be used.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Its effectiveness varies because of bait shyness.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cholecalciferol naturally occurs as vitamin D3 in many foods, including fish.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It was developed as a poison to control rats and mice in the 1980s.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It works by leaching calcium from the bones of the poisoned animal into its bloodstream, leading to organ failure.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cholecalciferol will reduce populations of possums and rats, but not stoats, since it does not bioaccumulate in animals.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It breaks down readily in the environment and the risk of by-kill is considered to be low.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Cholecalciferol is more expensive to produce than 1080.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Some promising results have been obtained by combining cholecalciferol with other substances, such as aspirin, to make it more cost-effective and faster acting.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Para-aminopropiophenone (PAPP) was developed to control stoats, weasels, and feral cats, and registered for use in New Zealand in 2011.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It kills by preventing red blood cells from carrying oxygen.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] PAPP kills stoats directly, but not possums and rats.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It is approved for use in paste form or in fresh minced meat, so will only provide effective stoat control as part of intensive ground control.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The risk of by-kill is likely to be low since it does not leave residues in the environment.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Zinc phosphide (microencapsulated zinc phosphide paste) has been widely used overseas for decades, predominantly to control rats and mice on agricultural land.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It causes death by heart or respiratory failure.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In August 2011, the New Zealand Environmental Protection Authority approved the import and manufacture of microencapsulated zinc phosphide (MZP paste) as an alternative to 1080 for the ground control of possums.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] The application was made by Pest Tech Limited, with support from Connovation Ltd, Lincoln University, and the Animal Health Board.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It will be used as an additional vertebrate poison in certain situations.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Unlike 1080, it cannot be used for aerial application.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Sodium nitrite is a naturally occurring substance commonly used as a meat preservative, but toxic at higher doses.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It kills in a similar way as PAPP, by reducing the ability of red blood cells to carry oxygen (methemoglobinemia).
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Sodium nitrite is expected to be registered for use in for killing possums, but not rats.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It will not control stoats because it will not knock down rat populations or bioaccumulate in poisoned animals.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] It does not leave residues in the environment and the risk of by-kill is expected to be low.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Ground operations of which trapping is an important component have been shown to help populations of native birds.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Possums, rats, and stoats can all be killed with traps.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] However, an intensive ground operation will typically involve trapping possums and stoats, but poisoning rats because there are so many more of them and they reproduce quickly.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In a mass event, populations of rodents rapidly increase as much as ten-fold, and traps simply cannot be deployed rapidly enough or in sufficient numbers to knock them down.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Some terrain is too rugged or dangerous for trapping, and trapping is not practical on a large scale.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] In one day, a single trapper can check traps on tens of hectares, whereas an aerial 1080 drop can cover tens of thousands of hectares.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Once a trap has 'snapped', it will not catch another animal unless it is reset.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Traps need to be checked and reset regularly, which makes them labour-intensive.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Self-resetting traps, such as the Goodnature trap, are being developed and trialled, and could in the future significantly reduce labour costs and increase the cost-effectiveness of ground control operations.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Twenty three species of native birds have been reported as having been killed by leg-hold traps, and many kiwi have suffered leg or beak damage.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] These traps are now required to be set up off the ground on conservation land where kiwi or weka (which are ground-dwelling birds) live.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Biological control has been likened to the 'Holy Grail' of pest control by a number of sources, and was a major focus for research funding during the 1990s and 2000s in both New Zealand and Australia.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] Most of the methods proposed involved some form of genetic engineering, and if developed further would attract a great deal of public opposition.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1080-usage-in-new-zealand] No biological control method has therefore yet gained widespread acceptance as a viable alternative to 1080.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Broadcast from its Auckland studios, 1News' nightly 6pm bulletin is usually New Zealand's most-watched television programme and seen as influential.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] TVNZ operates bureaus in Auckland, Wellington and Christchurch and has foreign correspondents based in Australia, Europe and the United States.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Television news in New Zealand began in 1960 with the introduction of television broadcasting.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] News bulletins were produced separately in Auckland, Wellington, Christchurch and Dunedin, as the country's television stations initially operated independently due to the lack of a permanent national network.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Although temporary nationwide links could be established for major events, these required extensive advance planning and could only originate from predetermined locations.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] National news and current affairs programmes produced in Wellington were copied onto videotape and flown to the other centres for broadcast, often resulting in significant delays.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Plans for a nationwide television network were developed from 1967.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The proposed system would link the four main centres using a combination of microwave and off-air relay stations, allowing programmes to be broadcast simultaneously throughout the country from any of the major studios.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The sinking of the passenger ferry *Wahine* in April 1968 highlighted the limitations of the existing system.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Footage filmed in Wellington could not be broadcast simultaneously in other centres, and the extra-tropical cyclone associated with the disaster grounded aircraft, preventing videotapes from being flown around the country for later transmission.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In October 1969 the nationwide TV network was completed, using a mixture of microwave and off-air broadcast links.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The first network news broadcast was live on 3 November 1969 at 7:35pm, read by Dougal Stevenson; the programme was called the *NZBC Network News*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Initially, it was read by Philip Sherry, Dougal Stevenson or Bill Toft on a rotating roster.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Because the microwave network was not yet fully complete, footage from outside Wellington had to be inserted by manually switching between transmitter feeds.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] During these changes, viewers briefly saw a black slide carrying a letter in the top-right corner, usually hidden by television overscan.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The letter identified the source channel and signalled transmitters when to switch feeds.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Prior to the building of the Warkworth satellite communications station in 1971, international programmes could not be received live – the footage had to be flown into New Zealand and was often days old.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The *NZBC Network News* featured many other newsreaders until the NZBC was dissolved in 1975.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The programme was then renamed as simply *News*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] While the NZBC began broadcasting in colour on 31 October 1973, *Network News* continued to primarily broadcast in black-and-white until the NZBC was dissolved on 31 March 1975.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] This was to avoid refitting the Wellington studio in Waring Taylor Street with colour equipment while awaiting the move to the new purpose-built Avalon television centre.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] TV One began broadcasting on 1 April 1975 and moved its evening news bulletin to 6:30 pm, with Dougal Stevenson or Bill McCarthy reading the news on a rotating roster until 15 February 1980.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The launch of TV One also coincided with the opening of the Avalon television centre, allowing the news to broadcast primarily in colour.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] TV2 followed suit on 30 June 1975 and its main evening news was initially broadcast at 7 pm before moving to the earlier timeslot of 6 pm by the end of 1975.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Jennie Goodwin was the first female newsreader in New Zealand to anchor a nightly television news programme, although Angela D'Audney was the first two years earlier.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] TV One and South Pacific Television were amalgamated into Television New Zealand on 16 February 1980 and its main evening news continued to broadcast at 6:30 pm on TV One.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Initially, these programmes aired at 7:30 pm and ran for half an hour in duration.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In February 1982, the main bulletin was revamped and broadcast from 6:30-7:30 pm; the one-hour package incorporated the day's national and international news, regional news programmes and the weather forecast.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In late 1983, *Nationwide* was dropped, with the main bulletin extended to fill the time and give greater sports news coverage.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] During the mid-1980s, Philip Sherry and Tom Bradley shared the role of newsreader on a rotating roster with Richard Long and Tony Ciprian alternately presenting sports news.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Weather was presented on alternate nights by Veronica Allum and Sue Scott.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The main bulletin was revamped in November 1986 and renamed as the *Network News*, with Judy Bailey and Neil Billington initially co-presenting in a double-headed format and replacing Philip Sherry.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Tom Bradley moved to weekends, where he alternated with Angela D'Audney as weekend anchor.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In February 1988, sports anchor Richard Long took over from Neil Billington as co-anchor of the *Network News*, the beginning of a partnership that would continue for much of the next 15 years.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Tony Ciprian moved to the new commercial network TV3, the network's first sports producer.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] He was with *3 News* for almost 20 years.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In July 1988, the *Network News* was moved to 6 pm and renamed as the *Network News at Six* but the weekend bulletin remained at 6:30 pm (as the *Network News and Sport*).
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The moving of the *Network News* to 6 pm also marked the introduction of computer-generated weather graphics and the arrival of Jim Hickey and Penelope Barr, who replaced Veronica Allum and Sue Scott as weather presenters.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 3 April 1989 TVNZ launched a new nightly current affairs programme, *Holmes*, which was presented by Paul Holmes.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] At the same time, the duration of the *Network News at Six* was reduced back to 30 minutes and the regional news programmes were transferred to around 5:45 pm on TV2.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The year saw the introduction of TVNZ's first foreign correspondents – Liam Jeory in London and Susan Wood in Sydney.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In October 1989, the weekend *Network News and Sport* was moved from 6:30 pm to 6 pm.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In November 1989, the *Network News* was relaunched as *One Network News*; its renaming due to competition from new broadcasting station TV3's news programme *3 National News*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In December 1989, both *Top Half* and *Today Tonight* were axed by TVNZ but *The Mainland Touch* and *The South Tonight* continued for another year and screened on TV One at 5:45 pm as a lead-in to *One Network News* at 6 pm, with support from NZ On Air.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The Christchurch and Dunedin based regional news programmes were axed at the end of 1990.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In February 1995, the main bulletin was again extended from 30 minutes to a full hour, screening from the now familiar 6 pm timeslot, followed by *Holmes* at 7 pm.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The change coincided with the unveiling of a new studio set which was used until 2003.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 2 January 1995, the main *One Network News* bulletin was delayed for 10 minutes after protesters occupied the studio and protested about the Māori language bulletin *Te Karere* which was off air over the Christmas and New Year period.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] July 1997 saw the replacement of weekend news presenters Angela D'Audney and Tom Bradley with husband and wife Simon Dallow and Alison Mau.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Bradley resigned, but D'Audney stayed as a backup presenter for other bulletins until her death in 2002.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 11 August 1997, the early morning *Telstra Business* and *Breakfast* shows were first aired; Telstra Business was hosted by Michael Wilson; Breakfast hosted by Susan Wood and Mike Hosking.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In 1998, TVNZ signed *3 National News* anchor John Hawkesby to replace Richard Long from the start of 1999.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] But when Haweskby began presenting *One Network News* at 6 pm alongside Judy Bailey, there was a public outcry over the separation of Bailey and Long, that lead to Long reinstated as co-anchor at 6 pm three weeks later.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Hawkesby later took TVNZ to court, a dispute that he subsequently won.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The programme was renamed again on 31 December 1999 to *One News*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 19 March 2000, TVNZ launched its first digital initiative nzoom.co.nz.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Staffed by 20 journalists, nzoom included news, sports, entertainment and home and garden sections, in additional to being a web portal.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The website was closed in 2003, and replaced by a more basic offering that was designed to extend television programming.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] At the time of its closure, it ranked second amongst local online news providers - behind the New Zealand Herald and ahead of Stuff.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] 2003 saw a major shake up of TVNZ's news and current affairs programming with entering head Bill Ralston making sweeping changes to the formats of many programmes.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] A new state-of-the-art studio came into use for *One News* programmes, but many presenters were culled.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The changes saw the end of Long and Bailey's 15-year partnership; from January 2004, the main 6 pm bulletin reverted to a single-headed broadcast with Judy Bailey as anchor.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Jim Hickey, TVNZ's most popular weather presenter, and sports presenter April Bruce (née Ieremia) also left in 2003.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In October 2005, TVNZ announced that it would not be renewing long-standing flagship broadcaster Judy Bailey's contract; some observers believe this was a direct reaction to the programme's market share decline in Auckland to *3 News*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] An emotional Bailey signed off for the final time at the end of the 6 pm *One News* bulletin on 23 December 2005.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] She was TVNZ's longest serving newsreader and had been reporting and presenting with both NZBC and TVNZ for 34 years.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] When the 6 pm edition of *One News* returned after the Christmas break of 2005–2006, it reverted to double-headed presentation with Wendy Petrie and Simon Dallow taking over from Bailey.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The weekend 6 pm bulletin remained single-headed until September 2008, when popular presenter Peter Williams joined Bernadine Oliver-Kerby as co-anchor.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In December 2008, One News relaunched online news product under the TVNZ.co.nz domain.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The broadcaster said it was "upping the ante" for digital offerings.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Sir Paul Holmes returned to TVNZ as the host on the new political programme *Q+A* in 2009.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] He hosted the programme until late 2012, when illness prevented him from continuing his duties.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 3 November 2009, TVNZ celebrated One News' 40th birthday with some archival footage available on their website.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Later that year, Jennie Goodwin, David Beatson, Dougal Stevenson and Lindsay Perigo returned to read one *Breakfast* news segment each.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] A Saturday edition of *Breakfast*, called *Saturday Breakfast*, was broadcast from 3 September 2011, hosted by Rawdon Christie and Toni Street, and ran until the end of 2012, when it and *One News at 4:30* were cancelled for financial reasons.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] 1News was awarded Best News in the Qantas Media Awards from 2008 through 2011 and won Best Breaking News in the New Zealand Film and Television Awards 2012.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In September 2012 an announcement was made that TVNZ would discontinue *Close Up* at the end of 2012.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The final *Close Up* programme screened on 30 November 2012 and in early 2013, an announcement was made of the replacement show, named *Seven Sharp*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The first show screened on 4 February 2013.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Former BBC meteorologist Daniel Corbett joined the weather team in September 2014.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In December 2014, Jim Hickey left his position as head weather forecaster.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Nearly a year later Karen Olsen left the weathercaster position, making her final broadcast on 16 November 2015.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In July 2015, TVNZ rebranded its news website to One News Now, focused specifically on breaking news and video content.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The change was expected to double the website's number of video views.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Some changes were criticised for an apparent pivot towards "clickbait".
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In May 2016, TVNZ began syndicating news video with Stuff.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] One News programmes were renamed 1News in 2016, when TV One was renamed TVNZ 1.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] During the COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand as part of cost-cutting measures, 1News reverted to a single news presenter for its 6 pm bulletin.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Simon Dallow remained as the sole newsreader while Wendy Petrie lost her role.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Petrie would remain at TVNZ as a backup presenter across other 1News programmes.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Paul Yurisich, who was appointed to the role of Head of News and Current Affairs in 2020, resigned from TVNZ in 2022 after a review into the hiring of former Al Jazeera presenter Kamahl Santamaria.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Phil O'Sullivan replaced Yurisich as the Executive Editor, News and Current Affairs.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] O'Sullivan had previously been in the role in an acting capacity since June 2022.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In late July 2023, 1News revamped its intro and banner, by changing the colour from blue to black, and moving the name and job to the left side.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In early March 2024, TVNZ proposed ending several television programmes including "1News at Midday" and "1News Tonight" due to a decline in advertisement revenue and competition from digital competitors such as Netflix and YouTube.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] In addition, TVNZ has proposed 68 job cuts, amounting to about 9 percent of its staff.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 9 April, TVNZ confirmed that 1News' Midday and late night bulletins would be axed by mid-May 2024.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Midday broadcast its final bulletin on Friday 3 May 2024, hosted by Indira Stewart.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 7 October 2024, TVNZ's management proposed closing down 1News' website by February 2025 as part of a NZ$30 million cost-saving measure.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 29 October, TVNZ abandoned plans to shut down its 1News website but proposed expanding the news content of its TVNZ+ streaming service.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 26 January 2026, 1News updated its template with minor changes to graphics.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] On 10 May 2026, 1News further advanced its appearance with a new opening, a new desk and a refreshed background including a virtual studio and purple colour scheme instead of their traditional blue.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] BNZ Business Breakfast airs at 6:00am, 30 minutes, Before *Breakfast*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Mei Heron will bring together business news, market updates, and expert perspectives to help make sense of the day ahead.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The bulletin has five segments separated by advertisement breaks.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] National and international news stories for the first three segments (approximately 35 minutes), sport news in the fourth segment (approximately 10–15 minutes) with weather at the end.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] with the full show starting from 6:30am.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Discontinued in July 2012, when TVNZ 7 closed down.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] Discontinued in 2013 due to lack of funding.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] During the COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand a 1News Special was broadcast most days at 1 pm.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] During the 1 pm broadcast Director-General of Health Ashley Bloomfield would announce how many new cases of coronavirus were in New Zealand.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] The following is a list of 1News reporters.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] This list does not include reporters from *20/20*, *Q+A*, *Fair Go*, *Sunday*, *Te Karere*, *Marae*, *Breakfast* and *Seven Sharp*.
[src:akatarawa-forest/1news] TVNZ has one of the largest news gathering teams in the country – based in New Zealand and in TVNZ bureaus around the world.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2001-wellington-regional-council-election-p01] Elections for the regional councils of New Zealand were held from September to 13 October 2001 as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2001-wellington-regional-council-election-p01] 134 regional councillors were elected across all 12 regions.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2010 Wellington Region local elections** were part of the 2010 New Zealand local elections, to elect members to sub-national councils and boards.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] These elections covered the Wellington Region council (known as the Greater Wellington Regional Council), eight territorial authority (city and district) councils, three district health boards, and various community boards and licensing trusts.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] As per the Local Electoral Act 2001, all the elections occurred on Saturday 9 October 2010.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Greater Wellington Regional Council (GWRC) is the regional council covering the whole Wellington Region.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] It represents a population of 478,600 as of the Statistics New Zealand's June 2009 estimate, and consists of thirteen councillors elected from six constituencies (Wellington, Lower Hutt, Porirua-Tawa, Kāpiti Coast, Upper Hutt, Wairarapa) using the First Past The Post voting system.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Wellington constituency returns five members to the GWRC.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Porirua-Tawa constituency returns two members to the GWRC.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] One member from the Kapiti constituency was elected to GWRC.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent Nigel Wilson retained the seat against former Kāpiti Coast District councillor Ann Chapman.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] One member from the Wairarapa constituency was elected to GWRC.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Former Carterton District Council mayor Gary McPhee won the constituency, defeating incumbent Ian Buchannan.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2016** **Greater Wellington Regional Council election** was a local election held from September to 8 October in the Greater Wellington region of New Zealand as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Voters elected 12 councillors for the 2016–2019 term of the Greater Wellington Regional Council.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Postal voting and the single transferable vote system were used.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillor Judith Aitken did not seek re-election.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbents Sue Kedgley, Chris Laidlaw and Daran Ponter were re-elected, joined by former Wellington City deputy mayor Ian McKinnon and Roger Blakeley.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillors Ken Laban and Prue Lamason were re-elected, while David Ogden defeated incumbent councillor Sandra Greig.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillors Jenny Brash and Barbra Donaldson were re-elected.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Retiring Kapiti Coast District Council councillor Penny Gaylor was elected, defeating incumbent councillor Nigel Wilson.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillor Paul Swain was elected unopposed.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Wairarapa constituency was vacant following the death of councillor Gary McPhee in June 2016.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Retiring South Wairarapa mayor Adrienne Staples was elected.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2019** **Greater Wellington Regional Council election** was a local election held from 20 September until 12 October in the Greater Wellington region of New Zealand as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Voters elected thirteen regional councillors for the 2019–2022 term of the Greater Wellington Regional Council.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] By July 2019 four councillors had announced that they would not be standing for re-election to the Wellington Regional Council; Sue Kedgley, Chris Laidlaw, Ian McKinnon and Paul Swain.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The GWRC has been "under fire" for changes to the bus services, particularly in Wellington city.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Names in bold font identify successful candidates.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2022 Greater Wellington Regional Council election** was a local election held from 16 September until 8 October in the Greater Wellington region of New Zealand as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Voters elected thirteen regional councillors for the 2022–2025 term of the Greater Wellington Regional Council.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The election was held using the single transferable vote system.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Thirteen councillors were elected across six constituencies.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] All five incumbent councillors stood for re-election.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Roger Blakeley and Glenda Hughes were unsuccessful.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] David Lee, Thomas Nash, and Daran Ponter were re-elected.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] They were joined by Simon Woolfe and Yadana Saw.
[src:akatarawa-forest/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Daran Ponter, a Labour councillor, was elected as chair unopposed.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] The park is owned and managed by Greater Wellington Regional Council, making it one of the largest landowners in New Zealand.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa is a Māori name meaning 'Trailing vines'.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] Activities include cycling, hunting, fishing, horse riding, 4WD-vehicle trips and trail biking, including at the Karapoti Gorge.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa Forest has ancient northern rātā which predate human habitation of New Zealand, including one tree which is believed to be 1100 years old.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] Some of these trees are wider than Tāne Mahuta.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] One is largest rātā tree in New Zealand, at 39 metres tall.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] Greater Wellington Regional Council carried out a 1080 dropping programme in 2013 to reduce pest species.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] A trailbiker was seriously injured in the park in July 2017.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] A dirt-biker was rescued from the forest in February 2021.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] Between December 2017 and August 2018, a 1.7 kilometre zig-zag track that is part of the Cannon Point Walkway was closed to the public due to a disagreement between Upper Hutt City Council and a private landowner over land access.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] In early 2021, Forest and Bird campaigned for Upper Hutt City Council to keep a 35-hectare block as a wildlife corridor and reserve, connecting Akatarawa Forest with Wainuiomata.
[src:akatarawa-forest/akatarawa-forest] In July 2021, a further 1080 operation was carried out in 2021 to combat a resurgence in possum numbers.
